Title: EM_id0002_Drosophila_brain_region_5dTensor.rds
Description: 5D arrays with the binary label for the image segmentation. The training and test datasets are two stacks of 30 sections from a serial section Transmission Electron Microscopy (ssTEM) data set of the Drosophila melanogaster first instar larva ventral nerve cord (VNC). The microcube measures 2 x 2 x 1.5 microns approx., with a resolution of 4x4x50 nm/pixel. The corresponding binary labels are provided in an in-out fashion, i.e. white for the pixels of segmented objects and black for the rest of pixels (which correspond mostly to membranes). But it does not include the ground truth of test dataset.

Title: LM_id0001_DIC_C2DH_HeLa_4dTensor.rds
Description: 4D arrays with the multi-labels for the image segmentation. Human HeLa cells on a flat glass. The original dataset for 2D segmentation was provided by Dr. G. van Cappellen, Erasmus Medical Center, Rotterdam, The Netherlands. The dataset images were captured by the Zeiss LSM 510 Meta with the Objective lens, Plan-Apochromat 63x/1.4 (oil). The captured region is 0.19 x 0.19 microns, and the pixel size is 512x512 pixels per image. The time step is 10 min. To read them as the rds file, the original tif images were converted to the PNG images with 8-bit/16-bit grey scale using ImageJ/Fiji.

Title: EM_id0003_J558L_4dTensor.rds
Description: The mouse B myeloma cell line J558L derived from a BALB/c strain. Ultra-thin (approx. 90 nm) sections were examined in a Philips/FEI CM10 (80 kV) electron microscope equipped with a Bio-scan Camera Model 792. Images were recorded with Digital Micrograph software (Gatan). The imaging magnification is x5800.
DataProvider: Pattern Recognition and Image Processing, University of Freiburg. (https://lmb.informatik.uni-freiburg.de/resources/datasets/tem.en.html)

Title: EM_id0004_PrHudata_4dTensor.rds
Description: The primary human T cell isolated from peripheral blood mononuclear cells (PBMCs). The purity of the isolated cell fraction was determined by anti-CD3 staining and was 96%. Ultra-thin (approx. 90 nm) sections were examined in a Philips/FEI CM10 (80 kV) electron microscope equipped with a Bio-scan Camera Model 792. Images were recorded with Digital Micrograph software (Gatan).  The imaging magnification is x10500-34000.
DataProvider: Pattern Recognition and Image Processing, University of Freiburg. (https://lmb.informatik.uni-freiburg.de/resources/datasets/tem.en.html)
